<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1898-04-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1898-04-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="121" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d121">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Denby</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Sherman</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Peking, China</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1898-04-20"><hi rend="italic">April 20,
                                1898</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 2917.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inform you that
                            Kwangchau Bay, which has been recently ceded to the French Government
                            for ninety-nine years, is situate on the southwestern coast of China, in
                            the district of Leichou, Kwangtung Province.</p>
                        <p>The harbor is said to be a good one. The country back of it is highly
                            productive. One of the chief products is sugar.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Denby.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>